      - Minimal reasoning comments are allowed ONLY when required to justify expected-value derivation (e.g. loop count formula, boundary operator evaluation, break/continue path).
      - Any other explanatory comments are forbidden.
      - Branch-Intent Comment:
        - For EVERY @Test method, MUST include exactly ONE branch-intent comment line inside the // Arrange section using this exact format: // INTENT: <predicate>
        - <predicate> MUST be one of:
          - "no-branch" (only if focal method has no branches), OR
          - a concrete boolean predicate describing the targeted branch condition(s), using operators exactly as in code.
        - Allowed operators in INTENT predicates:
          - MAY use: >, >=, <, <=, ==, !=, &&, ||, parentheses.
          - MAY use `%` ONLY when focal method branch condition itself uses `%` (e.g. `i % 2 == 0`).
          - If focal method does NOT use `%`, MUST NOT introduce `%` in INTENT.
        - Intent-Operator Fidelity Rule:
          - The INTENT predicate MUST use the same comparison operators as the targeted source condition(s).
          - MUST NOT replace a strict comparison target (`>` / `<`) with an equality-based intent (e.g. `Q == T + 1`) unless source branches on equality.
        - MUST NOT use "no-branch" if focal method contains any branch/loop. If test targets a zero-iteration path (loop not entered), MUST express it as a concrete predicate such as `loopBound == 0` (or the exact compared expression, e.g. `value.length() == 0`).
        - If focal method contains any comparison/loop-count logic, <predicate> MUST include:
          - Concrete numeric values for loop bounds and witness indices used by this test (when loop is involved).
          - Operator(s) as written in source (including `%` if present in source).
        - Threshold numeric values in INTENT are OPTIONAL when they are derived from other runtime quantities (e.g. `T = other.length() + c`). If thresholds are omitted from INTENT, MUST still compute them in code and enforce the intended region by construction.
        - If the INTENT line is missing or not in the exact format, output is invalid and MUST be rewritten.
        - Loop Witness Intent Rule:
          Supersedes:
            - Continue/Else-If Ladder Witness Rule
            - Intent Feasibility Gate
            - Branch Coverage via Witness Selection
          - If focal method contains loop and test targets any loop-internal branch (including continue/break ladders), the INTENT predicate MUST:
            - Include the concrete loop bound value used by test (e.g. `value.length() == N`).
            - Include at least one concrete witness iteration for loop index (e.g. `i == i0`).
            - Include the targeted branch predicate at that witness using operators exactly as in source.
            - If branch is not the first in an else-if/continue ladder, include explicit negations of ALL earlier conditions at the witness, also written using operators exactly as in source.
          - The INTENT predicate MUST be logically satisfiable (no contradictions).
          - Witness Selection Feasibility Rule:
            - When targeting a non-first branch in a priority ladder, MUST choose a witness index value that can satisfy the targeted predicate together with all required negations of earlier predicates.
            - MUST NOT choose a witness index that makes any earlier ladder predicate true.
          - Witness Selection Construction Rule:
            - When the targeted predicate involves arithmetic constraints on witness variable (e.g. modular/divisibility, ranges, equalities), MUST choose a concrete witness value that satisfies the full INTENT conjunction by construction.
            - MUST prefer the smallest non-negative witness value that satisfies:
              - The targeted predicate.
              - All required negations of earlier ladder predicates.
              - Loop range constraints.
            - If no such witness exists for the chosen bound, MUST change bound source (or choose a different witness) rather than changing expected only.
          - After //INTENT, MUST compute in code the quantities referenced by INTENT (bound, i0, thresholds).
          - Witness-Bound Alignment Gate:
            - If INTENT includes a concrete bound value (e.g. `B == N`), MUST construct bound source so that runtime value of `B` equals `N`.
            - If INTENT includes `i == i0`, MUST ensure `0 <= i0 < B` by construction.
            - MUST NOT write an INTENT whose bound/witness pair is inconsistent with the constructed inputs.
          - Witness-Bound Minimality Rule:
            - If test targets a witness iteration `i == i0` inside loop whose header is of the form:
              - `for (int i = start; i < bound; i++)` then MUST choose/construct runtime `bound` so that `bound >= i0 + 1` (and `start <= i0`) by construction.
            - If loop uses `i <= bound`, MUST choose/construct runtime `bound` so that `bound >= i0`.
            - MUST NOT use out-of-range witnesses (e.g. `i == bound`, `i == bound + 1`) to describe branch that occurs inside loop body.
            - If witness is out of range, MUST rewrite test by changing witness and/or the constructed bound source (not by changing expected only).
          - Witness-Feasibility Gate:
            - INTENT MUST NOT contain contradictions at the witness.
            - MUST choose witness values and bounds so the INTENT predicate is satisfiable by construction.
            Details: See Witness Contradiction Examples for contradiction patterns.
          - If INTENT specifies any concrete numeric value (e.g. a bound `N` or witness `i0`), MUST assign that number to a local variable and use that variable to construct runtime inputs/stubs so runtime values match INTENT exactly (single source of truth for numbers).
          - MUST construct inputs so loop executes witness iteration by construction (no auxiliary asserts).
          - Forbidden vague INTENT:
            - MUST NOT write an INTENT that omits witness (e.g. only `i % 2 == 0`).
          - Witness Does Not Truncate Expected Rule:
            - A witness iteration in INTENT is used only to guarantee reachability of a targeted branch.
            - Unless focal method performs an iteration-shortening exit (`break`/`return`/`throw`) before completing the loop, expected MUST include the effects of all executed iterations, not only witness iteration.
          - `%` usage restriction: MAY use `%` in INTENT ONLY when focal method branch condition itself uses `%`.
          - Nested-if region intents: If targeting a region among multiple thresholds, INTENT MUST include concrete numeric values for lhs/rhs/thresholds and must state the full region predicate including the negation(s) that prevent deeper branches.
        - Intent-Bound Equality Rule:
          - If INTENT specifies a concrete bound value (e.g. `bound == N` or `value.length() == N`), test MUST construct bound source so that runtime bound equals N exactly.
          - MUST NOT write an INTENT bound that differs from the constructed runtime bound.
        - Nested-If Intent Completeness Rule:
          - If the targeted behavior is inside nested `if` blocks, the INTENT predicate MUST describe a satisfiable region that guarantees reachability:
            - include the derived quantity `Q` value used by test (as a concrete number),
            - include the relevant threshold values (as concrete numbers),
            - include the outer guard(s) needed to reach the nested block,
            - and include negation(s) of stronger nested guards when test targets a non-deepest region.
          - MUST NOT use an INTENT that mentions only an inner guard while omitting the outer guard(s) required for reachability.
        - Witness Range & Consistency Gate:
          - If INTENT mentions loop index witness (e.g. `i == i0`), then:
            - `i0` MUST be within the executed iteration range of focal method loop by construction.
            - For canonical loops `for (int i = start; i < bound; i++)`, MUST ensure `start <= i0 && i0 < bound`.
            - For loops with `i <= bound`, MUST ensure `start <= i0 && i0 <= bound`.
            - For descending loops, MUST ensure `i0` is within the descending range per the exact loop header.
          - INTENT MUST NOT contain contradictions at the witness.
          - MUST NOT use out-of-range witnesses (e.g. `i == bound`, `i == bound + 1`) to describe a break/continue that happens inside the loop.
          Details: See Witness Contradiction Examples for contradiction patterns.
        Region-Intent Normal Form: Superseded by: Monotonic-Threshold Accumulation Rule
        Continue/Else-If Ladder Witness Rule:
          Superseded by: Loop Witness Intent Rule
        Intent Feasibility Gate:
          Superseded by: Loop Witness Intent Rule
        Branch Coverage via Witness Selection:
          Superseded by: Loop Witness Intent Rule
        - Witness Contradiction Examples:
          - Non-exhaustive examples of contradictions in an INTENT predicate at a witness:
            - value simultaneously constrained to be equal to two different constants (e.g. `X == 0 && X == 1`)
            - a predicate and its negation both required at the same witness (e.g. `P && !P`)
            - mutually exclusive relational constraints on the same expression (e.g. `E > K && E <= K`)
            - a modular/divisibility constraint that is impossible for the chosen witness value (e.g. `X == c` combined with a `%` constraint that does not hold for `c`)
          - MUST choose witness values and bounds so the INTENT predicate is satisfiable by construction.
      - Witness Construction Without Extra Asserts:
        - When test targets a loop-internal branch using a witness iteration (e.g. `i == i0`), MUST guarantee witness reachability and predicate satisfaction by CONSTRUCTION, not by adding extra assertions.
        - Therefore MUST NOT add assertions such as:
          - `assertTrue(0 <= i0 && i0 < bound)`
          - `assertTrue(i0 % 2 != 0)` (or similar precondition checks) because they are auxiliary assertions unrelated to focal method output.
        - This prohibition also applies to non-loop tests: MUST NOT add `assertTrue/False` to validate branch preconditions (e.g. `assertTrue(Q > T)`); enforce by construction.
        - Instead, MUST:
          - compute `bound` and `i0` as local variables immediately after the INTENT line,
          - choose `bound` so that loop executes `i0`,
          - choose `i0` so that the intended branch predicate (and earlier-condition negations for ladders) is satisfiable,
          - and embed the same predicates only in expected-value simulation (not as separate asserts).

    Versions:
      - Java: 11
      - JUnit: 4.13.2
      - Mockito: 2.28.2
      - PowerMockito: 2.0.9

    Version Constraints:
      - DO NOT use JUnit 5 annotations (e.g. @BeforeEach, @DisplayName).
      - DO NOT use Mockito 3.x+ features (e.g. mockConstruction, mockedStatic).
      - DO NOT use Java 17+ features (e.g. record, sealed class).

