      - The code block MUST contain a single JUnit4 test class.
      - The test class name MUST be {FocalClassName}Test.
      - The test class MUST be in the same package as focal class (use the provided package).
      - MUST include all required imports so test compiles.
      - MUST NOT include any text outside the Java code block.
      - The generated test code MUST NOT contain "@Override".
      - The generated test code MUST NOT contain "extends {FocalClassName}".
      - The generated test code MUST NOT contain an anonymous subclass of focal class, including patterns like:
        - "new {FocalClassName}(){"
        - "new {FocalClassName}(" followed by "{"
      - The generated test code MUST NOT stub fields using Mockito/PowerMockito (e.g. "when(obj.field)..."). Fields are not methods.
      - Before output, internally verify the generated code does NOT contain:
        - "@Override"
        - "extends {FocalClassName}"
        - "new {FocalClassName}(){"
        - "new {FocalClassName}(" followed by "{"
        - "when(obj.field)"
        If present, MUST rewrite test to remove them and use whenNew/Whitebox/Mockito instead.
      - MUST NOT output any self-check results, verification logs, or explanations. MUST output only final Java code block per Output -> Format/Constraints.
      - Before output, MUST internally run a self-check on the generated code and rewrite until all checks pass:
        - No "@Override"
        - No "extends {FocalClassName}"
        - No anonymous subclass of focal class ("new {FocalClassName}(" followed by "{")
        - No field stubbing patterns like "when(<id>.<id>)" or "PowerMockito.when(<id>.<id>)"
        - No unqualified inner/nested class type declarations (e.g. `InnerClass X = ...;`); all must be `EnclosingClass.InnerClass`.
        - No missing imports for reflection simple names: Method, Constructor, Field.
        - If the provided source code contains any non-JDK "new X(...)", then test code MUST contain "PowerMockito.whenNew(X.class)"
        - Static call handling:
          - Determine whether X is JDK using Input -> Information -> Imports:
            - If there is an import starting with `java.`, `javax.`, `org.xml.`, `org.w3c.`, or `org.ietf.jgss.` then X is JDK.
          - If X is JDK:
            - The test code MUST NOT contain:
              - `PowerMockito.mockStatic(X.class)`
              - `PowerMockito.stub(PowerMockito.method(X.class,`
              - `@PrepareForTest({` with `X.class` included
            - MUST execute the real JDK method.
          - If X is NOT JDK:
            - The test code MUST contain `PowerMockito.mockStatic(X.class)` AND `PowerMockito.stub(PowerMockito.method(X.class, ...))` per the existing rules.
      - Output Expected-Value Compliance Check (REFERENCE ONLY):
        - The authoritative rules for expected-value construction are in "Expected Value Derivation Rules".
        - MUST internally verify compliance and MUST NOT introduce new expected-building approaches.
        - MUST NOT output any compliance confirmation text; output only final Java code block.
        - If focal method contains a priority chain inside a loop, internally verify:
          - expected is built via per-iteration simulation loop with complete ladder (including default),
          - no hand-written expected literals for loop-produced suffix,
          - no manual per-index append lists.
      - JDK Static Call Rewrite Template:
        - If any type used in focal method is classified as JDK by the above "DETERMINISTIC CLASSIFICATION", MUST follow this exact rewrite template and MUST NOT add PowerMockito runner/PrepareForTest for those JDK classes:
          - Remove:
            - `@RunWith(PowerMockRunner.class)` IF it exists only for JDK static mocking
            - `@PrepareForTest({ ..., <any java.*, javax.*, org.xml.*, org.w3c.*, or org.ietf.jgss.* class>, ... })`
            - any `PowerMockito.mockStatic(<any java.*, javax.*, org.xml.*, org.w3c.*, or org.ietf.jgss.* class>)`
            - any `PowerMockito.stub(PowerMockito.method(<any java.*, javax.*, org.xml.*, org.w3c.*, or org.ietf.jgss.* class>, ...))`
          - Keep test deterministic by choosing concrete inputs and asserting the real computed result.
        - This template has higher priority than any other rule that suggests mocking static calls.

  Global Rules (Stability First):
    - MUST prefer deterministic inputs and outputs.
    - MUST NOT rely on test execution order.
    - MUST NOT use Thread.sleep, current time, random, filesystem, network.
    - MUST NOT assert overly specific values unless guaranteed by stubs or literals in source code.
    - If a called method body is not provided and cannot be stubbed legally (e.g. method on a private inner class instance), MUST NOT invent an expected literal. MUST compute expected deterministically via reflection from a real instance (e.g. instantiate the private inner class reflectively and invoke the same method), then assert equality with focal method result.
    - MUST avoid flaky verifications (timing, concurrency, unordered collections) unless source code guarantees determinism.
    - MUST NOT override any method of focal class in tests, including focal method.
    - MUST NOT override, re-implement, wrap, or subclass focal class (including "new FocalClass(){...}", "extends FocalClass").
    - MUST call focal method on a real constructor (e.g. "new FocalClass(...)") instance and execute the real implementation in every test.

  Branch Coverage Rules:
    - Assertion statements exclusion:
      - Java `assert` statements MUST NOT be treated as branches to cover.
      - Tests MUST remain passing whether assertions are enabled or disabled.
    - MUST cover ALL branches that are reachable under deterministic control of:
      - Method inputs.
      - Stubs/mocks allowed by these rules.
    - If branch is reachable only via non-deterministic/environmental behavior that is forbidden to simulate, MUST not target it and keep suite stable (no failing tests).
    - For if/else-if/else chains: MUST create at least one test that enters each branch.
    - For switch: MUST create at least one test for each case and default (if present).
    - For ternary (?:): MUST create tests for both outcomes.
    - For try/catch/finally:
      - MUST create at least one test for the normal path (no exception).
      - MUST create at least one test for each catch block ONLY if you can deterministically trigger that exception using:
        - Deterministic input values, OR
        - Deterministic stubs/mocks
      - MUST NOT introduce unrealistic or environment-dependent behavior just to trigger exceptions.
      - If a catch block is logically reachable but cannot be deterministically triggered from available controls, MUST still keep test suite passing and prioritize stability.
    - For loops: MUST cover zero-iteration (if possible), single-iteration, and multi-iteration paths when logically reachable and deterministic.

  Boundary Value Construction Rules (to hit branches reliably):
    - For conditions using >, <, >=, <=:
      - MUST choose inputs that deterministically enter the intended branch.
      - Prefer minimal distance from boundary:
        - For x > k: use x = k + 1
        - For x >= k: use x = k
        - For x < k: use x = k - 1
        - For x <= k: use x = k
    - Derived-Quantity Strict-Boundary Construction:
      Superseded by: Strict-Inequality Input Construction Rule
      when: strict-inequality targeting
      - If branch condition compares a DERIVED QUANTITY `Q` (e.g. `string.length()`, `collection.size()`, arithmetic expression) against a THRESHOLD `T` using a strict operator (`>` or `<`), then for any test targeting that branch outcome MUST:
        - compute `Q` and `T` (and any offsets used to form `T`) as local variables,
        - choose the nearest satisfying value for `Q`:
          - to satisfy `Q > T`: set `Q = T + 1`
          - to satisfy `Q < T`: set `Q = T - 1` (domain-valid)
        - construct the input(s) deterministically from the chosen `Q` (repeat/size construction/etc.), not by hand-written literals.
      - MUST NOT rely on visually counted literals to satisfy strict inequalities.
    - If multiple conditions are chained (else-if): MUST ensure the chosen input satisfies target condition and fails all earlier conditions.
    - Boundary Self-Check:
      - For every test targeting branch controlled by length/number comparisons, MUST compute the compared values in test (e.g. int a = input.length(); int b = value.length();) and base expected construction on those computed values (not on assumed lengths).
      - Loop Bound Self-Check Gate:
        - If focal method contains loop `for (int i = 0; i < <boundExpr>; i++)`:
          - MUST compute `int bound = <boundExpr>;` in test (e.g. `int len = value.length();`).
          - If no iteration-shortening exit (`break`/`return`/`throw`) is reachable for the chosen inputs/stubs, MUST construct expected so that the number of loop-produced tokens equals `bound` exactly (even if `continue` exists).
          - If an iteration-shortening exit (`break`/`return`/`throw`) is reachable, expected MUST represent exactly the executed prefix up to the exit point and MUST NOT assume `bound` iterations.
          - If `bound == 0`, expected MUST equal the initial value before loop (no appends).
          - Before output, MUST self-check that expected construction matches the actually executed iteration count (full `bound` only when early-exit is proven unreachable; otherwise prefix-until-exit).
    - For compound boolean conditions (&&, ||): MUST create tests that cover each short-circuit outcome when logically reachable and deterministic.
    - Comparison-Driven Boundary Input Synthesis:
      - If focal method branches on any comparison of the form: LHS > RHS, LHS >= RHS, LHS < RHS, LHS <= RHS, LHS == RHS, MUST synthesize test inputs by selecting values at and around boundary of RHS.
      - MUST explicitly compute boundary value in test using local variables, e.g.: int lhs = ...; int rhs = ...; (or long) and then choose inputs that make comparison deterministically true/false.
      - For strict comparisons:
        - To satisfy `LHS > RHS`: choose LHS = RHS + 1
        - To satisfy `LHS < RHS`: choose LHS = RHS - 1 (only if valid for the domain)
      - For non-strict comparisons: To satisfy `LHS >= RHS` or `LHS <= RHS` or `LHS == RHS`: choose LHS = RHS
      - For nested comparisons with offsets (e.g. LHS > RHS + c1, LHS > RHS + c2, ...):
        - Let thresholds be T1 = RHS + c1, T2 = RHS + c2, ...
        - To target the region "LHS > Ti but NOT > Tj (j>i)", choose: LHS = Ti + 1 AND LHS = Tj (if that makes NOT > Tj true), otherwise choose LHS = Ti + 1 and verify it does not exceed the next threshold by construction.
        - In practice, for integer domains, SHOULD pick representative points:
          - LHS = (RHS + c) + 1 for each threshold c
          - and also one point at LHS = RHS (or RHS - 1) for the false path.
      - Domain-safe construction:
        - MUST NOT rely on visually counting characters in string literals to achieve a length.
        - If LHS is a string length, MUST construct the string with repeat: String s = "a".repeat(targetLen);
        - If test targets a strict-true branch on string length (e.g. len > threshold), SHOULD set targetLen using arithmetic (threshold + 1) and build the string via repeat(targetLen).
        - If LHS is a collection size, MUST construct it deterministically to target size.
        - If LHS is numeric input, MUST pass the numeric value directly (no parsing tricks).
    - Intent-Driven Threshold Template:
      - If the // INTENT predicate contains an offset threshold of the form:
        - lhs > rhs + c
        - lhs >= rhs + c
        - lhs < rhs + c
        - lhs <= rhs + c
        - then in code MUST compute:
          - int threshold = rhs + c;
          - and choose lhs using:
            - for strict true (>, <): lhs = threshold ± 1 (nearest satisfying value)
            - for non-strict true (>=, <=): lhs = threshold
        - MUST derive actual input object from lhs deterministically (repeat/size construction/etc.).
    - No-Manual-Length Literals:
      - If any branch condition depends on string length, MUST construct strings using repeat(targetLen).
      - MUST NOT use hand-written string literals (e.g. "testing", "abcde") to hit length boundaries.
    - Nested-Threshold Boundary Selection Rule:
      - If nested conditions compare the same derived quantity `Q` against multiple thresholds with strict operators, MUST choose `Q` values that land in the intended region using nearest-boundary construction: to satisfy `Q > Tk` and falsify `Q > T(k+1)`, choose `Q = Tk + 1` and ensure `Q <= T(k+1)`.
      - MUST construct input from `Q` deterministically (repeat/size construction/etc.).

  Mocking Decision Rules:
    - Use Mockito for normal dependency objects and their instance methods.
    - Use PowerMockito ONLY when required for:
      - static method mocking
      - static field replacement
      - constructor interception (whenNew)
      - private method stubbing on focal class spy
    - MUST NOT use PowerMockito for normal dependency instance method mocking.
    - MUST NOT use PowerMockito unless focal method or its called code requires it.
    - Instance Method Stubbing Preference:
      - If intercepting a constructor with PowerMockito.whenNew(X.class) and return mock instance `xMock`
      - MUST stub instance methods on `xMock` using Mockito (e.g. `Mockito.when(xMock.m(...)).thenReturn(v)`), NOT by using PowerMockito.stub(PowerMockito.method(X.class, ...)) and NOT by PowerMockito.mockStatic(X.class), unless focal method actually calls a static method.

  Inner / Nested Class Rules:
    - MUST determine whether a type is an inner/nested class using the provided "Inner classes signature" of focal class.
    - MUST reference any inner/nested class type using the enclosing class name:
      - Use "EnclosingClass.InnerClass" in all type references (declarations, casts, Class literals).
    - Exception:
      - If the inner class is declared private, MUST NOT reference it as a type at all in test code (no "EnclosingClass.InnerClass", no "EnclosingClass.InnerClass.class"):
        - MUST use reflection:
          - Class<?> inner = Class.forName("<EnclosingClass>$<InnerClass>");
          - Constructor<?> c = inner.getDeclaredConstructor(<EnclosingClass>.class);
          - c.setAccessible(true);
          - Object innerObj = c.newInstance(enclosingInstance);
          - Method m = inner.getDeclaredMethod("<methodName>");
          - m.setAccessible(true);
          - Object expected = m.invoke(innerObj);
          - E.g.: "EnclosingClass.InnerClass" (NOT "InnerClass").
    - This rule also applies to Class literals and reflection/Whitebox usage: Use "EnclosingClass.InnerClass.class" (NOT "InnerClass.class") in Whitebox.setInternalState/getInternalState and any Class<?> references.
    - Self-check:
      - Before output, MUST scan the generated test code and ensure there is NO variable declaration using a simple inner class name.
      - Forbidden examples: `InnerClass X = ...;`
      - Required form: `EnclosingClass.InnerClass X = ...;`
      - If any forbidden example exists, MUST rewrite code to use the enclosing-class-qualified type everywhere.
    - Non-static Inner Class Rule:
      - If the inner class signature does NOT contain the keyword "static", it is a non-static inner class.
      - For non-static inner classes, MUST NOT use PowerMockito.whenNew(...) to intercept construction of the inner class.
      - If focal class holds a non-static inner class instance in field (including final fields initialized with "new"), MUST replace that field after creating focal class instance:
        - EnclosingClass target = new EnclosingClass(...);
        - EnclosingClass.InnerClass innerMock = Mockito.mock(EnclosingClass.InnerClass.class);
        - Mockito.when(innerMock.someMethod(...)).thenReturn(safeValue);
        - Whitebox.setInternalState(target, "fieldName", innerMock);
      - MUST NOT attempt to stub inner-class fields using Mockito (e.g. "when(innerMock.someField)").
      - Exception: If focal method only reads inner-class FIELDS (not methods) and those fields are declared `final` (primitive or String), MUST NOT replace the inner instance with mock regardless of whether the initializer value is visible in the source.
              - MUST NOT attempt to change a final field via Whitebox.setInternalState(...), because final primitive/String fields are compile-time constants that may be inlined by the compiler; Whitebox.setInternalState will not affect value seen by focal method.
              - MUST keep the real inner instance.
              - Expected value derivation MUST follow this exact structure:
                - 1) Create a real focal class instance: `FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);`
                - 2) Obtain the real inner instance:
                    `EnclosingClass.InnerClass inner = Whitebox.getInternalState(target, "fieldName");`
                - 3) Read field value from the real instance:
                    `FieldType expected = (FieldType) Whitebox.getInternalState(inner, "fieldName");`
                    For primitives: `int expected = (int) Whitebox.getInternalState(inner, "fieldName");`
                - 4) Call focal method and assert equality: `assertEquals(expected, result);`
              - MUST NOT assert an invented literal (e.g. 100, 200) even if the initializer value is visible in source, because compile-time inlining means test would be fragile to source changes.
              - MUST NOT use Whitebox.setInternalState to set a different value on final field.

    - Static Nested Class Rule:
      - If the inner/nested class signature contains the keyword "static", it is a static nested class.
      - Static nested classes MAY be treated like normal classes.
      - If source code contains a non-JDK new-expression for a static nested class (e.g. "new EnclosingClass.NestedClass(...)"), MUST intercept it using PowerMockito.whenNew(EnclosingClass.NestedClass.class) following the whenNew rules.

    - Compilation Safety Rules:
      - MUST NOT declare variables using an unresolved simple inner class name (e.g. "InnerClass mockInnerClass") unless it is explicitly imported and resolvable; prefer "EnclosingClass.InnerClass".
      - Before output, MUST verify that all inner/nested class references compile by using the "EnclosingClass.InnerClass" form consistently.

    - PowerMockito Runner Rules (Interaction):
      Details: See Imports Policy -> Annotation/Runner Policy

  Dependency Stubbing Rules:
    - For every dependency call listed in Dependencies (method dependencies), MUST stub it.
    - If a dependency method returns value used later, MUST stub it to a safe non-null value.
    - If a dependency method is void, MUST stub it with Mockito.doNothing() unless it must throw.
    - If focal method calls the same dependency method multiple times, MUST provide stable behavior (same return) unless source code requires different returns.
    - MUST NOT create stubs that depend on call order unless source code explicitly requires it.

  Field Injection / Replacement Rules:
    - MUST use org.powermock.reflect.Whitebox.setInternalState for setting fields when direct injection is not available.
    - MUST import org.powermock.reflect.Whitebox
    - For instance fields:
      - Create object instance first, then Whitebox.setInternalState(instance, "fieldName", value)
    - For static fields: Whitebox.setInternalState(TargetClass.class, "fieldName", value)
    - Static Field Handling Rule:
      - If field in focal class or its inner/nested classes is declared `static`, MUST treat it as a static field even if accessed via instance expression (e.g. `inner.b`).
      - MUST NOT set a static field on instance (forbidden pattern): Whitebox.setInternalState(instance, "staticFieldName", value)
      - MUST set it on the declaring class: Whitebox.setInternalState(DeclaringClass.class, "staticFieldName", value)
      - If focal method reads a static field, MUST NOT attempt to change outcome by replacing instance that appears to own it; MUST change the static field value on class instead.
    - MUST NOT use Java reflection to set fields (Field#set is forbidden).
    - MUST NOT use Mockito.when(...) or PowerMockito.stub(...) for field values (fields are not methods).
    - If focal method reads field (e.g. obj.field), MUST control it deterministically.
      - Default: control it by setting field value using Whitebox.setInternalState(...) or by constructing object with the desired field value.
      - Exception:
        -if field is declared `final` (especially primitive/String) and the provided Input does NOT include its initializer value (e.g. only `final int b` is known), MUST NOT:
          - invent value (e.g. 100) and assert it, OR
          - attempt to change it via Whitebox.setInternalState(...), OR
          - replace the owning object with mock and expect final field value to change.
          - Instead, MUST derive `expected` from the real runtime object state using Whitebox getters and assert equality:
            - FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);
            - Object owner = Whitebox.getInternalState(target, "ownerFieldName");
            - <Type> expected = (<Type>) Whitebox.getInternalState(owner, "fieldName");
            - assertEquals(expected, target.{focalMethod}(...));
    - Mandatory Imports: org.powermock.reflect.Whitebox
    - If a dependency is mock and focal method reads field from it (e.g. ex.a), MUST set field value using Whitebox.setInternalState(mockOrInstance, "{fieldName}", value). MUST NOT use Mockito/PowerMockito stubbing for fields.
    - When focal method reads field (pattern: obj.field, not followed by "("), MUST control it using this exact structure and order:
      - OwnerType owner = ...;  # real instance or mock instance
      - Whitebox.setInternalState(owner, "fieldName", value);
      - FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);  # if needed, after whenNew setup
      - Object result = target.{focalMethod}(...);
    - MUST NOT write code like:
      - when(obj.field).thenReturn(...)
      - PowerMockito.when(obj.field).thenReturn(...)
      - doReturn(...).when(obj.field)
      - stub(method(obj.field))
    - If focal method source code contains field access token ".<fieldName>" that is NOT followed by "(" (i.e. not method call), MUST NOT use Mockito/PowerMockito stubbing for it and MUST use Whitebox.setInternalState(...) to control it.
    - Final Primitive/String Compile-time Constant Exception:
      - If the accessed field is declared `final` AND is a primitive or String (compile-time constant), MUST NOT:
        - Attempt to change it via Whitebox.setInternalState(...) with any value, OR
        - Replace the owning object with mock and expect the constant to change, OR
        - Hardcode expected value as literal even if the initializer is visible in source (the inlined value is what focal method sees; asserting literal couples test to source constant and is forbidden).
      - This applies regardless of whether the owner:
        - Focal class itself
        - A non-static inner class instance held by focal class
        - An external class instance held as field of focal class
      - MUST always derive `expected` from the real runtime object state using one of these two equivalent patterns (choose based on field accessibility):
        - Pattern A : field is accessible via Whitebox:
          - FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);
          - OwnerType owner = (OwnerType) Whitebox.getInternalState(target, "ownerFieldName"); (omit if field is directly on focal class)
          - int expected = (int) Whitebox.getInternalState(owner, "fieldName");
          - assertEquals(expected, target.{focalMethod}(...));
        - Pattern B : Whitebox is insufficient or field is on an external class instance:
          - FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);
          - Field ownerField = FocalClass.class.getDeclaredField("ownerFieldName");
          - ownerField.setAccessible(true);
          - Object owner = ownerField.get(target);
          - Field constField = owner.getClass().getDeclaredField("fieldName");
          - constField.setAccessible(true);
          - int expected = constField.getInt(owner);
          - assertEquals(expected, target.{focalMethod}(...));
      - MUST prefer Pattern A when it produces correct results. Use Pattern B when Pattern A returns an incorrect value due to compile-time inlining (i.e. when field value seen by focal method differs from Whitebox-read value).
      - This exception overrides the generic "control fields via setInternalState" instruction for all final primitive/String fields.

  Partial Mocking Rules (Focal Class):
    - MAY create spy of focal class to stub focal-class internal methods (excluding focal method).
    - MUST NOT stub focal method itself.
    - Prefer Mockito stubbing for non-private focal-class methods on the spy:
      - Mockito.doReturn(value).when(spy).method(args)
      - Mockito.doNothing().when(spy).voidMethod(args)
    - Use PowerMockito ONLY for private methods on focal class: PowerMockito.when(spy, "privateMethodName", args).thenReturn(value)
    - MUST NOT use PowerMockito.doReturn().when().

  Partial Mocking Rules (Inner Class Instances / Private Methods)
    - If focal method calls a private method on object that is stored in a focal class field (including a non-static inner class instance), and the private method implementation/spec is not provided, MUST stub that private method via spy of the real field instance.
    - MUST use this exact structure and order (per test method):
      - FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);
      - Object inner = Whitebox.getInternalState(target, "fieldName");
      - Object innerSpy = PowerMockito.spy(inner);
      - Whitebox.setInternalState(target, "fieldName", innerSpy);
      - PowerMockito.when(innerSpy, "privateMethodName", ...).thenReturn(safeValue);
      - Object result = target.{focalMethod}(...);
    - MUST NOT attempt any of these (they either DO NOT compile or are forbidden):
      - Mockito.when(innerMock.privateMethod()).thenReturn(...)
      - PowerMockito.doReturn(...).when(innerSpy, "privateMethodName", ...)
      - Stubbing private methods by referencing them directly in Java code (private access violation).
    - If the private method has no parameters, MUST stub it with: PowerMockito.when(innerSpy, "privateMethodName").thenReturn(value);
    - If the private method has parameters, MUST include argument matchers deterministically: PowerMockito.when(innerSpy, "privateMethodName", Mockito.any(Type.class), ...).thenReturn(value);

  PowerMockito Activation Rules:
    - PowerMockito usage is allowed ONLY when required for:
      - static method mocking of NON-JDK classes
      - constructor interception (whenNew) for NON-JDK classes
      - private method stubbing via PowerMockito.when(spy, "privateMethod", ...)
      - static field replacement that requires @PrepareForTest (if applicable)
    - If PowerMockito is used in test class:
      - MUST add @RunWith(PowerMockRunner.class)
      - MUST add @PrepareForTest(...) with only the necessary non-JDK classes per existing rules
    - If PowerMockito is NOT used in test class:
      - MUST NOT add @RunWith(PowerMockRunner.class)
      - MUST NOT add @PrepareForTest(...)
    - Note: imports for PowerMockito/PowerMockRunner/PrepareForTest/Whitebox may still exist due to Imports Policy, but annotations MUST remain conditional as above.

  Static Method Mocking Rules (PowerMockito) (ENFORCED):
    - JDK Static Methods Rule:
      - MUST NOT mock static methods of any JDK class (i.e. any class whose fully-qualified name starts with `java.`, `javax.`, `org.xml.`, `org.w3c.`, or `org.ietf.jgss.`).
      - Therefore MUST NOT use PowerMockito.mockStatic(...) or @PrepareForTest(...) for any `java.*`, `javax.*`, `org.xml.*`, `org.w3c.*`, or `org.ietf.jgss.*` class.
      - For JDK static calls, MUST execute the real methods and assert results derived from deterministic inputs.
    - If mocking any static method:
      - MUST use:
        - @RunWith(PowerMockRunner.class)
        - @PrepareForTest({ ... })
      - MUST call PowerMockito.mockStatic(TargetClass.class) before stubbing.
      - MUST stub static methods ONLY with stub(method()) pattern:
        - PowerMockito.stub(PowerMockito.method(TargetClass.class, "methodName")).toReturn(value)
        - With parameters: PowerMockito.stub(PowerMockito.method(TargetClass.class, "methodName", ParamType.class, ...)).toReturn(value)
      - MUST NOT use:
        - PowerMockito.when(TargetClass.method()).thenReturn(...)
        - Mockito.mockStatic / MockedStatic
        - PowerMockito.stub(TargetClass.class, "methodName").toReturn(value)

  Constructor Interception (whenNew) Rules (PowerMockito):
    - Constructor Interception Policy:
      - This section is the single source of truth for whenNew usage.
      - MUST NOT apply any unconditional rule such as "intercept every new" or "always use withAnyArguments".
      - whenNew is used only to keep tests deterministic and side-effect-free.
    - Constructor Chain Identification Step:
      - Before writing each @Test, identify constructor chains executed by focal method, including nested constructions: Example form: `new Outer(new Inner(args...))` or deeper `new A(new B(new C(...)))`.
      - For each chain, list constructors from innermost -> outermost.
    - Chain Contract Declaration (per-test):
      - At the start of each @Test (in comments is fine), declare the executed constructor chain(s) and the interception plan:
        - Example:
          - `// CHAIN: Inner(argsFromFocalInputs) -> Outer(Inner)`
          - `// INTERCEPT: whenNew(Inner).withArguments(exactArgsFromFocalInputs), whenNew(Outer).withAnyArguments`
      - The test code MUST match this declared contract. If it does not, rewrite before output.
    - Constructor Interception Completeness Rule:
      - MUST intercept ALL constructors in an executed chain. Partial interception is forbidden.
      - Exception: if an inner constructor throws making later ones unreachable, omit later interceptions.
    - Inner-First Rule (chain order):
      - For any nested/layered chain `new Outer(new Inner(args...))`, interception MUST be configured inner-first:
        - 1) `whenNew(Inner.class).withArguments(exactArgs...).thenReturn(innerMock or thenThrow(...));`
        - 2) `whenNew(Outer.class).withAnyArguments().thenReturn(outerMock);`  (wrapper-any is allowed)
      - Forbidden: Intercepting only the outer/wrapper constructor while leaving the inner constructor real.
    - Argument Matching Rules:
      - MUST NOT use Mockito matchers inside `whenNew(...).withArguments(...)`: Forbidden: `withArguments(any(...))`, `withArguments(eq(...))`, `withArguments(argThat(...))`
      - Innermost constructors: MUST use `withArguments(exact...)` from focal method inputs.
      - `withAnyArguments()`: allowed ONLY for outer/wrapper constructors or truly unobservable args.
      - Argument Derivation Rule (no invented args):
        - The `exactArgs...` used in `whenNew(Inner).withArguments(exactArgs...)` MUST be directly derived from:
          - focal method parameters, OR
          - local variables that are direct aliases of those parameters (e.g. `String filename = inputFilename;`).
        - MUST NOT introduce a different literal/value for interception than the one passed to focal method call.
    - Declared-Exception-Only Rule for whenNew(...).thenThrow(...): When using `whenNew(X.class)...thenThrow(e)`, the thrown exception type MUST be compatible with X's real constructor signature.
    - This rule applies to non-JDK new-expressions in:
      - focal method body
      - focal class constructor body
      - focal class field initializers (e.g. "private final Dep dep = new Dep();")
    - MUST NOT replace constructor-created dependencies by overriding, re-implementing, wrapping, or subclassing focal class or focal method.
    - MUST NOT use anonymous classes (e.g. "new FocalClass(){...}") or "extends FocalClass" in tests.
    - Canonical whenNew Template (single-constructor case):
      - Use this template ONLY when the production code has a single `new Dep(args...)` (not a nested chain):
        - Dep depMock = PowerMockito.mock(Dep.class);
        - Mockito.when(depMock.someMethod(Mockito.any())).thenReturn(safeValue);
        - PowerMockito.whenNew(Dep.class).withArguments(exactArgs...).thenReturn(depMock);
        - FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);   // after whenNew
        - Object result = target.{focalMethod}(...);
      - Template constraint:
        - Focal method MUST be invoked with the same variables used in `withArguments(exactArgs...)` (no divergence).
      - MUST NOT use `withAnyArguments()` here unless args are truly unobservable and explained.
    - Canonical whenNew Template (nested/layered chain case):
      - For `new Outer(new Inner(args...))`:
        - Inner innerMock = PowerMockito.mock(Inner.class);
        - Outer outerMock = PowerMockito.mock(Outer.class);
        - PowerMockito.whenNew(Inner.class).withArguments(exactArgs...).thenReturn(innerMock);
        - PowerMockito.whenNew(Outer.class).withAnyArguments().thenReturn(outerMock);
        - // stub methods on outerMock as needed
        - FocalClass target = new FocalClass(...);   // after whenNew
        - Object result = target.{focalMethod}(...);
    - Overload/Ambiguity Avoidance:
      - MUST NOT use PowerMockito.method(Class, "methodName", ...) for instance methods when mock instance exists.
      - MUST always stub instance method on the returned mock with Mockito to avoid method-resolution ambiguity.
    - Critical Order Rule: PowerMockito.whenNew(...) MUST be configured BEFORE creating focal class instance/spy.
    - If whenNew is used anywhere in test class:
      - MUST NOT create focal class instance/spy in @Before.
      - MUST create focal class instance/spy inside each @Test after whenNew setup.
    - Output-Time Gate (must pass before final output):
      - For each @Test:
        - If there is any `whenNew(Outer.class)` for a nested chain, there MUST be a corresponding `whenNew(Inner.class)` in the same test (unless Inner is forced to throw and Outer is unreachable).
        - MUST be ZERO occurrences of `withArguments(Mockito.` or `withArguments(any(` (matcher usage).
        - MUST be ZERO occurrences of `withArguments("...")` (string literal) if focal method is called with a different filename variable/value.
          - i.e., argument used in `withArguments(...)` MUST be the same variable/value passed to focal method call.
        - The test MUST contain the Chain Contract comment and code must satisfy it (manual consistency check).
      - If any gate fails, MUST rewrite; MUST NOT output failing code.

  PowerMockito API Consistency Rules
    - MUST NOT use PowerMockito.doReturn(...).when(...) in any test.
    - For private method stubbing MUST use only: PowerMockito.when(spyObj, "methodName", ...).thenReturn(value);

  PrepareForTest Rules (PowerMockito):
    - @PrepareForTest MUST include:
      - focal class IF you stub private methods on it, OR if it contains new statements to be intercepted
      - any class that contains static methods you mock
      - the caller class that executes new (NOT the instantiated class) for whenNew interception
    - MUST NOT include unrelated classes in @PrepareForTest.
    - If a non-JDK new-expression exists in a focal class field initializer, MUST include focal class in @PrepareForTest (because the new statement is executed during focal class instantiation).
    - If stubbing a private method on an inner/field object using PowerMockito spy, MUST include focal class in @PrepareForTest({FocalClass.class}) (because field is owned/initialized by focal class and is accessed/replaced via Whitebox).

  Test Class Structure Rules:
    - MUST generate the minimum number of tests required to cover all branches, but MAY add more if stable.
    - MUST include a stable "happy path" test if such a path exists.
    - MUST name test methods descriptively and uniquely.
    - MUST use Google Java Style Guide formatting.

  Assertions Rules (Stability First):
    - Prefer assertions that cannot flake:
      - assertNotNull(result) when result is expected non-null
      - assertEquals(expectedStubbedValue, result) when result is directly derived from stubs or literals
      - verify(mock).method(...) when side effects are expected
    - Avoid asserting exact strings/numbers unless they are stubbed or literal in source code.
    - Exception: If expected is computed deterministically inside test by mirroring focal method control flow (per Expected Value Derivation Rules), asserting exact strings/numbers is REQUIRED.
    - Exception expectation rule:
      - Use @Test(expected=...) ONLY when exception type is deterministically triggered under default JVM settings.
      - MUST NOT use AssertionError as an expected exception unless the production code explicitly throws it (i.e. not via Java `assert`).
      - If multiple exception types are possible depending on whether assertions are enabled, MUST avoid such test case or prefer expecting the non-assert runtime exception that occurs regardless of `assert`.